 We know the car in the fast lane traveled 480 miles in 60 hours. Since the car in the slow lane travels half of that speed, we can set up a proportion to find its speed. 

First, we find the speed of the car in the fast lane \text{Speed of the fast lane} = \frac{60 \text{ hours}}{2} = 30 \text{ miles/hour} 

Now, we can find the speed of the car in the slow lane \text{Speed of the slow lane} = \frac{30 \text{ miles/hour}}{2} = 15 \text{ miles/hour} 

Since the car in the slow lane takes 4 times longer to cover the distance than the car in the fast lane, we can calculate the time taken by the car in the slow lane using the ratio of their speeds \text{Time taken by the slow lane} = \frac{1}{4} \times \frac{480 \text{ miles}}{15 \text{ miles/hour}} 

 \text{Time taken by the slow lane} = 32 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, the car in the slow lane took 32 hours to cover the same distance as the car in the fast lane.
The answer is: 32 hours: 32 hours: 32 hours: 32 hours: 32 hours: 32 hours

